# Creating a NEW GitHub repo: the capability that taught us the most.
#
# It fails in a Claude Code cloud session for TWO independent reasons, and fixing
# either one alone changes nothing. This descriptor exists to stop an agent
# rediscovering that by hitting a 403.
#
#   1. CREDENTIAL TYPE. The built-in GitHub tools authenticate as the Claude
#      GitHub App, and a GitHub App installation token cannot create a user-owned
#      repo: POST /user/repos takes a user OAuth token or a PAT. -> 403
#      "Resource not accessible by integration".
#
#   2. EGRESS POLICY (the wall behind the wall). Even holding a valid user PAT,
#      the cloud session's agent proxy re-terminates TLS and filters GitHub API
#      *paths*, allowing only endpoints scoped to the session's configured repo.
#      POST /user/repos is not repo-scoped, so the proxy refuses it before it ever
#      reaches GitHub: "sessions are bound to their configured repositories."
#
# So "reachable" is true (api.github.com answers 200), the credential is right,
# and the call still cannot be made. Host-level reachability does not imply
# path-level reachability. Hence the Unless veto: in a cloud session this is
# unavailable no matter what token is present. Verified empirically, 2026-07-14.

Capability github.repo-create
  Description Create a NEW GitHub repository (needs a user credential AND an unfiltered egress path)
  Probe env GH_TOKEN
  Probe env GITHUB_TOKEN
  Probe file ~/.config/gh/hosts.yml
  Unless env CLAUDE_CODE_REMOTE
  Blocked Cloud session: the agent proxy filters GitHub API paths to this session's bound repo, so POST /user/repos is refused even with a valid PAT. A token does NOT fix this. Create the repo from a local session, or under an org, or make it in the GitHub UI and push into it from here (writes to an EXISTING repo are allowed).
  Requires A user credential (PAT or user OAuth; an App installation token is never enough for user-owned repos) AND an environment whose egress is not path-filtered.
  Remediation Create it from a LOCAL session (simplest, and what works today). Or create an org repo: POST /orgs/{org}/repos does work for the Claude GitHub App with Administration permission. Or create the empty repo in the github.com UI, then push into it from anywhere, since existing-repo writes pass the proxy. Adding a PAT as GH_TOKEN in cloud environment settings is NOT sufficient on its own and was verified to still 403 at the proxy.
  Risk high
  Environments local

Capability github.repo-write
  Description Read and write EXISTING repos (issues, PRs, comments, pushes) via the built-in GitHub tools
  Probe http https://api.github.com
  Requires The Claude GitHub App connection, or a gh token synced with /web-setup
  Remediation Works on the default Trusted network level, and repo-scoped API paths pass the cloud agent proxy. This is a different credential and policy class from creating a new repo: acting on the repo you are bound to is fine, minting a new one is not.
  Risk low
  Environments local cloud ci
